        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7451.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from St G. J. Mivart, 22 January 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7451.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from St G. J. Mivart, 22 January 1871</ref>. His first <ref target="" resp="#automat">letter to Mivart of 23 January 1871</ref> has not been found, but see the draft <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7453.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to St G. J. Mivart, [23 January 1871]</ref>, and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7454.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from St G. J. Mivart, 24 January 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In Mivart 1871a, p. 102, Mivart wrote, ‘Now, considering the number of instances adduced of sudden modifications in domestic animals, it is somewhat startling to meet with Mr. Darwin’s dogmatic assertion that it is “a <hi rend="italic">false belief</hi>” that natural species have often originated in the same abrupt manner.’ See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7425.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Francis Darwin, [after 21 January 1871]</ref> and n. 2, which relates to a similar claim by Mivart.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6018.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 5th ed.</ref> and <hi rend="italic">Variation.</hi></note>
        </div>        
            
